"A chill, metallic tang hung over the dunes as Maya Smith slipped out of her car, the parking lot bathed in the pale, sickly glow of sodium vapor lamps. The coastal air smelled of salt and something wilder—a heady mix that seemed to vibrate in sync with the low hum of distant traffic. She shouldered her camera bag, its contents jingling softly, and felt the familiar surge of nerves and anticipation. Tonight was the culmination of weeks of preparation. This was more than just a night for stargazing; it was a rite at the edge of the world, where the sky stretched impossibly wide over the waters of Port Jefferson.\n\nThe event had drawn a scattered crowd, huddled on blankets and logs scattered throughout the cobbled promenade. Laughter and the occasional gasp for breath floated through the cool night, mingling with the distant calls of gulls. Maya moved toward the central gathering near the lighthouse, scanning the faces for familiar faces—her collaborators, her students, a handful of strangers whose excitement she hoped would be as high as hers. Her mind flickered through checklists: filters aligned, lens caps secured, lenses calibrated. The astrophotography workshops she’d organized were finally underway, and her pulse quickened at the thought of seeing the stars through someone else’s eyes.\n\nA young woman in a black hoodie waved frantically as Maya approached. “You Maya, right?” she called, breath visible in the cold.\n\n“Yes,” Maya replied, her voice low but steady. She handed over a printed instruction sheet, then nodded toward a telescope set atop a stack of old firewood. “You ready?”\n\nThe second participant arrived—a tall man in a navy jacket, carrying a heavy tripod. He eyed the setup with professional skepticism, adjusting a lens with careful, practiced hands. Maya watched their exchange with a keen eye, reading tension as though it were a language. Was it nerves, or something deeper? She could feel the charged silence between them, a palpable expectation that threatened to crackle into something volatile.\n\nAs twilight deepened to indigo, the first constellations began to shimmer into view: Orion’s silhouette just visible above the tree line, the Milky Way’s faint arc barely skimming the horizon. A child’s giggle broke the tension, and the group grew more relaxed. Maya adjusted her camera’s ISO, mindful that every minute counted. These workshops were her calling, her way of bridging the vastness of the universe with the intimate act of capturing"